Simulation Study 1: Significance of Regression

Introduction

In this simulation study we will investigate the significance of regression test. We will simulate from two different models:

  1. The significant model

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2} + \beta_3 x_{i3} + \epsilon_i \]

where \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\) and

  • \(\beta_0 = 3\),
  • \(\beta_1 = 1\),
  • \(\beta_2 = 1\),
  • \(\beta_3 = 1\).
  1. The non-significant model

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2} + \beta_3 x_{i3} + \epsilon_i \]

where \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\) and

  • \(\beta_0 = 3\),
  • \(\beta_1 = 0\),
  • \(\beta_2 = 0\),
  • \(\beta_3 = 0\).

For both, we will consider a sample size of \(25\) and three possible levels of noise. That is, three values of \(\sigma\).

  • \(n = 25\)
  • \(\sigma \in (1, 5, 10)\)

We will use simulation to obtain an empirical distribution for each of the following values, for each of the three values of \(\sigma\), for both models.

  • The \(F\) statistic for the significance of regression test.
  • The p-value for the significance of regression test
  • \(R^2\)

For each model and \(\sigma\) combination, we will use \(2000\) simulations. For each simulation, we will fit a regression model of the same form used to perform the simulation.

We will use the data found in study_1.csv for the values of the predictors. These will be kept constant for the entirety of this study. The y values in this data are a blank placeholder.

We will have simulated the y vector \(2 (models)3 (sigmas)2000 (sims)=12000\) times.

Methods

Here We simulate from a significant model with different \(\sigma\) \(1000\) times to obtain an empirical distribution of the test statistic.

#setting seed
birthday = 19910130
set.seed(birthday)

#Importing data file for this simulation study
library(readr)
study_1 = read_csv("study_1.csv")

sample_size = 25

# set parameter for significant model
beta_0_sig = 3
beta_1_sig = 1
beta_2_sig = 1
beta_3_sig = 1
num_sim = 2000

x0 = rep(1, sample_size)

sigmas = list(1, 5, 10)

# function to simulate the data
library(broom)
sim_anova = function(study_1,
                     x0,
                     n,
                     beta_0,
                     beta_1,
                     beta_2,
                     beta_3,
                     sigma) {
  study_1$y = beta_0 * x0  + beta_1 * study_1[[2]] + beta_2 * study_1[[3]] + beta_3 * study_1[[4]] + rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sigma)
  model = lm(y ~ ., data = study_1)
  
  list(
    r_squ = glance(model)$r.squared,
    f_stat = glance(model)$statistic[[1]],
    p_val = glance(model)$p.value[[1]]
  )
}



# perform simulation with the $\sigma$ value of 1, 5, 10.

# use replicate to simulate 1000 times for sigma = 1
sig_stat_1 = replicate(
  n = num_sim,
  sim_anova(
    study_1,
    x0,
    sample_size,
    beta_0_sig,
    beta_1_sig,
    beta_2_sig,
    beta_3_sig,
    sigmas[[1]]
  )
)

#Storing results in data frame
r_2_1 = do.call(rbind, sig_stat_1[1,])
f_1 = do.call(rbind, sig_stat_1[2,])
p_1 = do.call(rbind, sig_stat_1[3,])

result_sigma1 = data.frame(r_squared = r_2_1,
                           f_statistic = f_1,
                           p_value = p_1)


# use replicate to simulate 1000 times for sigma = 5
sig_stat_2 = replicate(
  n = num_sim,
  sim_anova(
    study_1,
    x0,
    sample_size,
    beta_0_sig,
    beta_1_sig,
    beta_2_sig,
    beta_3_sig,
    sigmas[[2]]
  )
)

#Storing results in data frame

f_2 = do.call(rbind, sig_stat_2[2,])
p_2 = do.call(rbind, sig_stat_2[3,])
result_sigma2 = data.frame(r_squared = r_2_2,
                           f_statistic = f_2,
                           p_value = p_2)


# use replicate to simulate 1000 times for sigma = 10

Results

The plot show distributions of significant model \(F\) statistic, p-value and \(R^2\). we will discuss these results in discussion section.

The plot show distributions of non-significant model \(F\) statistic, p-value and \(R^2\), along with true distribution curve on the top.

The plot show distributions of \(F\) statistic, p-value and \(R^2\) from both non-significant model(blue) and significant model(grey), along with true distribution curve(orange) on the top.

Discussion

  • Do we know the true distribution of any of these values?

We know the true distribution of non-significant model. The non-significant model is the linear regression model under the null hypothesis.

The true distribution of \(R^2\) in non-significant model, under the null hypothesis is true, is

\[ R^2 \sim Beta\left (\frac {p-1}{2}, \frac {n-p}{2}\right) \]

The true distribution of \(F\) statistic in non-significant model, under the null hypothesis is true, is

\[ F \sim F_{p-1, n-p} \]

The true distribution of \(p\)-value in non-significant model, under the null hypothesis is true, is

\[ p \sim Unif(0,1) \]

From researching online, We could know the true distribution of significant model.

The true distribution of \(R^2\) in significant model, under the alternative hypothesis is true, is a non-central \(R^2\)-distribution

\[ R^2 \sim Beta\left (\frac {k-1}{2}, \frac {N-k}{2}, \lambda\right) \]

The true distribution of \(F\) statistic in significant model, under the alternative hypothesis is true, is a non-central \(F\)-distribution

\[ F \sim F_{k-1, N-k, \lambda} \] where \[\lambda = \sum_in_i(\mu_i - \bar\mu)^2\] and \[\bar\mu = \sum_in_i\mu_i/N\]

The true distribution of \(p\)-value in significant model, under the alternative hypothesis is true, is

\[ p \sim P( F_{k-1, N-k, \lambda} > F ) \]

  • How do the empirical distributions from the simulations compare to the true distributions?

We conducted simulations to generate the empirical distribution of estimates from non-significant models for different \(\sigma\) values. The \(F\) statistic histogram from these simulations appears to follow an F-distribution with (p - 1) = 3 degrees of freedom and (n - p) = 21 degrees of freedom. We verified this by comparing it to the curve of the true \(F\) statistic, which matched for all \(\sigma\) values.

Similarly, we observed that the p-values under the null are uniformly distributed between 0 and 1 for all three levels of \(\sigma\). This was confirmed by comparing the empirical distribution plot to a uniform distribution.

We also calculated \(R^2\) from the non-significant model during simulation and created a histogram of the empirical distribution. The curve of the true distribution, which follows a beta distribution with (p - 1) = 3 degrees of freedom and (n - p) = 21 degrees of freedom, matched the histogram for all \(\sigma\) values.

Overall, our simulations demonstrate that the distributions of \(F\) statistic, p-values, and \(R^2\) from non-significant model are consistent with their theoretical distributions for all levels of \(\sigma\).

  • How are each of the \(F\) statistic, the p-value, and \(R^2\) related to \(\sigma\)? Are any of those relationships the same for the significant and non-significant models?

\(F\) statistic: The \(F\) statistic is calculated by

\[ F = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(\hat{y}_{1i} - \bar{y})^2 / (p - 1)}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \hat{y}_{1i})^2 / (n - p)}, \]

As \(\sigma\) increases, the denomator increases, which leads to a decrease in the \(F\) statistic. A small value of the \(f\) statistic corresponds to a small portion of the variance being explained by the linear regression model.

\(p\)-value: The \(p\)-value is a probability that calcaulted by

\[ P(F_{p-1, n-p} > F) \]

under null hypothesis. As \(\sigma\) increases, the \(F\) statistic decreases, which leads to an increase in the \(p\)-value. When the p-value is lower than \(\alpha\) level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

\(R^2\): \(R^2\) is the proportion of observed variation in \(y\) that can be explained by the simple linear regression model..

\[ R^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^{n}e_i^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \bar{y})^2} \]

As \(\sigma\) increases, the variability of the response variable \(y\) increases, the denomator increases, which leads to a decrease in \(R^2\).

In analyzing the results from both significant and non-significant models, we observe that as the noise level increases, the distribution of test statistic from the significant model becomes more sensitive to the sigma. When the noise is large, the distribution of test statistic from the significant model is closer to that of the non-significant model. We also note that under the null hypothesis, the p-values are uniformly distributed between 0 and 1, while under the alternative hypothesis, they are skewed towards small values at the left. As the noise level increases in the model, we can clearly see that the R-squared distribution under the alternative hypothesis becomes right-skewed, from left skewed.

All three test statistic distributions of significant model are closer to that of the non-significant model while the noise level increases. These observations have important implications for statistical analysis. In particular, they highlight the importance of carefully considering noise levels when interpreting results from statistical models.

Simulation Study 2: Using RMSE for Selection?

Introduction

In this simulation study we will investigate how well the Test RMSE can be used to select the best model works. Since splitting the data is random, we dont expect it to work correctly each time. We could get unlucky. But averaged over many attempts, we should expect it to select the appropriate model.

We will simulate from the model

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2} + \beta_3 x_{i3} + \beta_4 x_{i4} + \beta_5 x_{i5} + \beta_6 x_{i6} + \epsilon_i \]

where \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\) and

  • \(\beta_0 = 0\),
  • \(\beta_1 = 3\),
  • \(\beta_2 = -4\),
  • \(\beta_3 = 1.6\),
  • \(\beta_4 = -1.1\),
  • \(\beta_5 = 0.7\),
  • \(\beta_6 = 0.5\).

We will consider a sample size of \(500\) and three possible levels of noise. That is, three values of \(\sigma\).

  • \(n = 500\)
  • \(\sigma \in (1, 2, 4)\)

We will use the data found in study_2.csv for the values of the predictors. These will be kept constant for the entirety of this study. The y values in this data are a blank placeholder.

Each time we simulate the data, we will randomly split the data into train and test sets of equal sizes (250 observations for training, 250 observations for testing).

For each, fit nine models, with forms:

  • y ~ x1
  • y ~ x1 + x2
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6, the correct form of the model as noted above
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7 + x8
  • y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7 + x8 + x9

For each model, calculate Train and Test RMSE.

\[ \text{RMSE}(\text{model, data}) = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i = 1}^{n}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2} \]

We will repeat this process with \(1000\) simulations for each of the \(3\) values of \(\sigma\). For each value of \(\sigma\), we will create a plot that shows how average Train RMSE and average Test RMSE changes as a function of model size. Also we will show the number of times the model of each size was chosen for each value of \(\sigma\).

We will have simulated the \(y\) vector \(31000=3000\) times. We will have fit \(931000=27000\) models.

Methods

We simulate the \(y\) vector \(31000=3000\) times. We then fit \(931000=27000\) models.

library(readr)
study_2 = read_csv("study_2.csv")

beta_0 = 0

library(tibble)

# define data generating processs
gen_slr_data = function(x, sample_size = 500, sigma) {
  x0 = rep(1, n = sample_size)
  y = 0 * x0  + 3 * x[[1]] - 4 * x[[2]] + 1.6 * x[[3]] - 1.1 * x[[4]] + 0.7 * x[[5]] + 0.5 * x[[6]] + rnorm(n = sample_size, mean = 0, sd = sigma)
  tibble(x0, x, y)
}

# function to obtain RMSE
rmse = function(actual, predicted) {
  sqrt(mean((actual - predicted) ^ 2))
}


# function to simulate entire dataset
sim_rmse = function(x = study_2, sigma_1) {
  sim_slr_data = gen_slr_data(x, sample_size = 500, sigma = sigma_1)
  # test-train split
  slr_trn_idx = sample(nrow(sim_slr_data), size = 0.5 * nrow(sim_slr_data))
  slr_trn = sim_slr_data[slr_trn_idx, ]
  slr_tst = sim_slr_data[-slr_trn_idx, ]
  # create a list of the models fit.
  mod_list = list(
  model1 = lm(y ~ x1, data = slr_trn),
  model2 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2, data = slr_trn),
  model3 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data = slr_trn),
  model4 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4, data = slr_trn),
  model5 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5, data = slr_trn),
  model6 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6, data = slr_trn),
  model7 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7, data = slr_trn),
  model8 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7 + x8, data = slr_trn),
  model9 = lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7 + x8 + x9, data = slr_trn)
  )
  
  # make predictions on the train data with each model
  mod_trn_pred = lapply(mod_list, predict, slr_trn)
  
  # make predictions on the test data with each model
  mod_tdt_pred = lapply(mod_list, predict, slr_tst)
  
  
  list(
  # calculate train RMSE
  slr_trn_rmse = sapply(mod_trn_pred, rmse, actual = slr_trn$y),
  # calculate test RMSE
  slr_tst_rmse = sapply(mod_tdt_pred, rmse, actual = slr_tst$y) 
  )

}


# perform simulation procedure for sigma value of 1,2, 4
rmses_1 = replicate(n = sim_size, sim_rmse(study_2, sigma[[1]]))
rmses_2 = replicate(n = sim_size, sim_rmse(study_2, sigma[[2]]))
rmses_4 = replicate(n = sim_size, sim_rmse(study_2, sigma[[3]]))

Discussion

  • Does the method always select the correct model? On average, does is select the correct model?

The method does not always select the correct model. On average, It does select the correct model.

The model selection plots above provide insight into which model was chosen as the best model and how many times. It is clear from these plots that the true model (model 6) was chosen more frequently than any other model, with 550, 512, and 338 selections for \(\sigma\) values of 1, 2, and 4 respectively. While the true model was the most commonly selected model overall, it is important to note that the simulations do not always choose the true model as the correct one.

Looking at the average test RMSE plots, which are generated from unseen data, we can see that the lowest average test RMSE for every \(\sigma\) value is associated with the true model (model 6). This suggests that, on average, our simulation process is able to identify the given true model as the best model.

Overall, these plots indicate that while the simulations may not always select the true model, on average, it does select the correct model.

  • How does the level of noise affect the results?

The average RMSE plots above shows that - as the level of \(\sigma\) values increases, the variation in average RMSE value decreases, but the average RMSE value increases. For \(\sigma = 1\), We see that the range of average test RMSE value is between 2.582 to 1.022 thats the length of 1.56. The same statistics for \(\sigma\) value 2 and 4 are 1.07 and 0.661 respectively. The average test RMSE for model 6 is 1.015, 2.029, 4.059 for \(\sigma\) value 1, 2 and 4. This is actually makes sense. When there is more noise in the response variable, the model has a harder time accurately capturing the underlying relationship between the predictors and the response. This leads to an increase in the models RMSE for both the training and test data. In other words, the model is less able to generalize from the training data to new, unseen data when there is more noise present.

The impact of noise on model accuracy is further illustrated in the model selection plots. As the level of noise increases, there is a greater chance that other models will be selected as the correct model, even though they may not accurately capture the true underlying relationship between the predictors and response. This means that there is less chance that the true model will be selected as the correct model when there is more noise present in the data.

In summary, as the level of noise increases, the models ability to accurately capture the underlying relationship between the predictors and the response decreases, which leads to an increase in the models RMSE.

Simulation Study 3: Power

Introduction

In this simulation study we will investigate the power of the significance of regression test for simple linear regression.

\[ H_0: \beta_{1} = 0 \ \text{vs} \ H_1: \beta_{1} \neq 0 \]

Recall, we had defined the significance level, \(\alpha\), to be the probability of a Type I error.

\[ \alpha = P[\text{Reject } H_0 \mid H_0 \text{ True}] = P[\text{Type I Error}] \]

Similarly, the probability of a Type II error is often denoted using \(\beta\); however, this should not be confused with a regression parameter.

\[ \beta = P[\text{Fail to Reject } H_0 \mid H_1 \text{ True}] = P[\text{Type II Error}] \]

Power is the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when the null is not true, that is, the alternative is true and \(\beta_{1}\) is non-zero.

\[ \text{Power} = 1 - \beta = P[\text{Reject } H_0 \mid H_1 \text{ True}] \]

Essentially, power is the probability that a signal of a particular strength will be detected. Many things affect the power of a test. In this case, some of those are:

  • Sample Size, \(n\)
  • Signal Strength, \(\beta_1\)
  • Noise Level, \(\sigma\)
  • Significance Level, \(\alpha\)

Well investigate the first three.

To do so we will simulate from the model

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \epsilon_i \]

where \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\).

For simplicity, we will let \(\beta_0 = 0\), thus \(\beta_1\) is essentially controlling the amount of signal. We will then consider different signals, noises, and sample sizes:

  • \(\beta_1 \in (-2, -1.9, -1.8, \ldots, -0.1, 0, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, \ldots 1.9, 2)\)
  • \(\sigma \in (1, 2, 4)\)
  • \(n \in (10, 20, 30)\)

We will hold the significance level constant at \(\alpha = 0.05\).

Use the following code to generate the predictor values, x: values for different sample sizes.

x_values = seq(0, 5, length = n)

For each possible \(\beta_1\) and \(\sigma\) combination, we will simulate from the true model at least \(1000\) times. Each time, we would perform the significance of the regression test.

It is possible to derive an expression for power mathematically, but often this is difficult, so instead, we rely on simulation.

Methods

For each possible \(\beta_1\) and \(\sigma\) combination, we simulate from the true model \(1000\) times. Each time, we perform the significance of the regression test and store the results.

library(dplyr)
#Setting the seed
birthday = 19910130
set.seed(birthday)

#set up parameters
sigmas = c(1, 2, 4)
n = list(10, 20, 30)
beta_0 = 0
beta_1s = seq(-2,2,by=0.1)
num_sims = 1000
alpha = 0.05

# function to generate x values
gen_x = function(n = 10) {
  seq(0, 5, length = n)
}

# create a list to store x_value for each sample size
x_value_lists = sapply(n, gen_x)

# generate different sigma and beta1 variable combinations for the function gen_mod
g = do.call(cbind, expand.grid( sigmas, beta_1s) )
colnames(g) = c("sigma", "beta_1")  
sim_g = g[rep(seq_len(nrow(g)), each = num_sims), ]

# function to generate model lists from different sigma and beta1 combinations
gen_mod = function(sample_size, sigma, beta_1) {
  x = x_value_lists[[sample_size / 10]]
  y = beta_0 + beta_1 * x + rnorm(sample_size,mean=0,sd = sigma)
  model = lm(y ~ x)
  summary(model)$coefficients[2, ]
}

# perform simulation procedure for sigma value of 1
sim_mod_list = mapply(gen_mod, n[[1]], sim_g[, 1], sim_g[, 2])

result = do.call(rbind, lapply(seq_len(ncol(sim_mod_list )), function(i) sim_mod_list [,i])) 

result = cbind(sample_size = rep(n[[1]], nrow(sim_g)), sim_g, result, power = result[, 4] < alpha)
# perform simulation procedure for sigma value of 2
sim_mod_list_2 = mapply(gen_mod, n[[2]], sim_g[, 1], sim_g[, 2])

result_2 = do.call(rbind, lapply(seq_len(ncol(sim_mod_list_2)), function(i) sim_mod_list_2[,i])) 

result_2 = cbind(sample_size = rep(n[[2]], nrow(sim_g)), sim_g, result_2, power = result_2[, 4] < alpha)
# perform simulation procedure for sigma value of 4
sim_mod_list_3 = mapply(gen_mod, n[[3]], sim_g[, 1], sim_g[, 2])

result_3 = do.call(rbind, lapply(seq_len(ncol(sim_mod_list_3)), function(i) sim_mod_list_3[,i])) 

result_3 = cbind(sample_size = rep(n[[3]], nrow(sim_g)), sim_g, result_3, power = result_3[, 4] < alpha)

results = rbind(result, result_2, result_3)

# store result for different plot

sig1 = as.data.frame(result) %>%
  group_by(sigma, beta_1) %>%
  summarise_at(vars(power), mean)

sig2 = as.data.frame(result_2) %>%
  group_by(sigma, beta_1) %>%
  summarise_at(vars(power), mean)

sig3 = as.data.frame(result_3) %>%
  group_by(sigma, beta_1) %>%
  summarise_at(vars(power), mean)

# store result for different plot

result = as.data.frame(result)
result_2 = as.data.frame(result_2)
result_3 = as.data.frame(result_3)
beta_0 = 0
beta_1 = -2
sigma_1 = 1
sigma_2 = 2
sigma_4 = 4

Sxx_10 = sum((x_value_lists[[1]] - mean(x_value_lists[[1]])) ^ 2)

beta_1_hats_10_1 = result[result$sample_size == 10 & result$sigma == 1 & result$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_10_2 = result[result$sample_size == 10 & result$sigma == 2 & result$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_10_4 = result[result$sample_size == 10 & result$sigma == 4 & result$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

Sxx_20 = sum((x_value_lists[[2]] - mean(x_value_lists[[2]])) ^ 2)

beta_1_hats_20_1 = result_2[result_2$sample_size == 20 & result_2$sigma == 1 & result_2$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_20_2 = result_2[result_2$sample_size == 20 & result_2$sigma == 2 & result_2$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_20_4 = result_2[result_2$sample_size == 20 & result_2$sigma == 4 & result_2$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

Sxx_30 = sum((x_value_lists[[3]] - mean(x_value_lists[[3]])) ^ 2)

beta_1_hats_30_1 = result_3[result_3$sample_size == 30 & result_3$sigma == 1 & result_3$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_30_2 = result_3[result_3$sample_size == 30 & result_3$sigma == 2 & result_3$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_30_4 = result_3[result_3$sample_size == 30 & result_3$sigma == 4 & result_3$beta_1 == -2, ]$Estimate


beta_1_hats_10_non = result[result$sample_size == 10 & result$sigma == 1 & result$beta_1 == 0 , ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_10_alt = result[result$sample_size == 10 & result$sigma == 1 & round(result$beta_1, 1)==0.5, ]$Estimate

beta_1_hats_10_alt2 = result[result$sample_size == 10 & result$sigma == 1 & result$beta_1 ==1, ]$Estimate

The Figure 4 show t-distributions of the \(\hat\beta_1\) Values under the Null( \(\beta_1\) = 0) and Alternative Hypotheses( \(\beta_1\) = 0.5 and \(\beta_1\) = 1, two just for comparsion)

Discussion

  • How do \(n\), \(\beta_1\), and \(\sigma\) affect power? Consider additional plots to demonstrate these effects.

Reducing \(\sigma\) value, increasing \(n\), and increasing absolute value of \(\beta_1\) will all reduce the overlap of the sampling distributions of the means, thus increasing power.

In both Figure 1 and 2, it demonstrate a clear pattern of symmetry around \(\beta_1 = 0\). As the absolute value of \(\beta_1\) increases, the statistical power gradually increases from very low (close to 0). At lower \(\sigma\) values, the power can reach to 1, while at higher \(\sigma\) values, much larger \(\beta_1\) values are required for power to approach 1. Increasing \(\sigma\) leads to a decrease in power. Within each panel, it is evident that larger sample sizes lead to greater power.

We can see the distributions of \(\hat{\beta_1}\) under Null and Alternative hypotheses as shown in Figure 3. Larger signal will shift the \(H_1\) curve away from the \(H_0\) curve, large \(n\) or smaller \(\sigma\) will both decrease \(SD[\hat{\beta_1}]\) and cause the curves to be narrower and taller.

We used t-value distribution under Null and Alternative hypothesis to understand how these parameters affect power. As shown in Figure 4, the absolute value of \(\beta_1\) increases, the non-centrality parameter (ncp) of the t-values under Alternative hypothesis will also increase. The alternative hypothesis t-distribution will shift toward the right, further away from the Null hypothesis t-distribution. This leads to the proportion of the shade area on the right of the critical value will also increase.

In Figure 5, As sample size increases, the shape of the Null hypothesis t-distribution will be taller and narrower, which is very close to normal distribution, with to a smaller critical value. At the same time, because \(S\_{xx}\) increases, \(SD[\hat{\beta_1}]\) decreases, results ncp to increase, shifting the Alternative hypothesis t-distribution to the right. Together, these effects lead to higher power.

As shown in Figure 6, when \(\sigma\) decreases, it decrease \(SD[\hat{\beta_1}]\), and thus increase ncp, shift the Alternative hypothesis t-distribution to the right, and increases power.

To summarize, higher statistical power is determined by larger sample sizes, stronger signals, and smaller noises.

  • Are \(1000\) simulations sufficient?

The results from Figure 1 and 2 indicate that the simulations performed are generally sufficient, with most curves appearing smooth. However, there are some exceptions, particularly in situations with smaller sample sizes and larger \(\sigma\) values. To investigate further, we extracted result from the simulated models and analyzed in Figure 7 and 8. The results show that, for the most part, the empirical mean of \(\beta_1\) approaches the expected value as more simulations are performed. Only in cases with smaller sample sizes and larger \(\sigma\) values (such as N = 10 and \(\sigma\) = 4) were the values not entirely stable, although they were not significantly off either. Overall, it appears that 1000 simulations are sufficient for the purposes of this study. However, in situations with smaller sample sizes and larger \(\sigma\) values, increasing the number of simulations may be beneficial. Despite these minor fluctuations, the simulations performed were deemed appropriate for the studys objectives.
